==English==

===Etymology===
From Old French word ''[[travailler]]'' meaning "to [[trouble]], to [[suffer]], or be worn out". See also '''[[travail]]'''.

===Pronunciation===
*{{audio|en-us-travel.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ævəl|-ævəl]]

===Verb===
{{en-verb|travels|'''[[travelling]]''' ''(British)'', '''[[traveling]]''' ''(American)''|'''[[travelled]]''' ''(British)'', '''[[traveled]]''' ''(American)''}}

# {{intransitive}} To be on a [[journey]], often for pleasure or business and with luggage; to go from one place to another.
#: ''I like to '''travel'''.''
# {{intransitive}} To [[pass]] from here to there; to move or [[transmit]]; to go from one [[place]] to another.
#: ''Soundwaves can '''travel''' through water.''
# {{cattag|intransitive|basketball}} To move illegally by walking or running without dribbling the ball.
# {{transitive}} To travel throughout (a place).
#: ''I’ve '''travelled''' the world.''

